        "text": "Jennifer Gauthiers\n\nFor many of us in the global North, the Pacific Islands seem like tiny specks in a huge ocean, very far away, hard to get to and quite isolated. Located in the geographic region known as Oceania, which includes Australia and New Zealand, the Pacific Islands comprise twenty-two separate countries and territories (IUCN). They are commonly divided into three groups Micronesia, Melanesia and Polynesia, which cover a land area of 376,000 square miles, putting their size just above Mozambique in a global ranking (IUCN; CIA, “Area”). The islands have a total population of around nine million people, similar to that of Honduras (CIA, “Population”). In mainstream discourse, the islands are promoted as little more than exotic tourist destinations. They are often portrayed as failing to produce anything of value and thus dependent on more powerful nations and NGOs (Hau’ofa, 1993: 4).\n\nIn his essay, “Our Sea of Islands” (1993), Tongan-Fijian writer and anthropologist Epeli Hau’ofa proposes a dramatic paradigm shift. Having grown up in the Pacific Islands and as a teacher of Pacific Islander students, Hau’ofa became frustrated by the limiting and dismissive language used to describe his homeland. Rather than thinking of the peoples of the Pacific as isolated in a small space and dependent on larger nations, he asks us to consider that the ancestors viewed their territory as vast and expansive:\n\nTheir universe comprised not only land surfaces, but the surrounding ocean as far as they could traverse and exploit it, the underworld with its fore-controlling and earth-shaking denizens, and the heavens above with their hierarchies of powerful gods and names stars and constellations that people could count on to guide their ways across the sea. (Hau’ofa, 1993: 7)\n\nTanam n°52/20i9"
